### Description

The new control flow is great. There are some users, like myself that find it a little messier looking, specifically the extra indentation, and braces. It makes it look more of a jumble of html and JS. I think a lot of users liked the fact that the templates looked like plain html using the old *ng directives. I understand the old syntax is still available. A solution would add an alternate short hand control flow  that utilizes html's existing indentation and block scope ( open/close tag). This will be most useful for small control flow one liners. 

### Proposed solution

This proposal does not change existing control flow. It adds a shorthand alternative. It allows control flow @ syntax to be used in html tags, and scope is determined by the tags open/close tags. 
 
  ``` 
<div @if(person1)>{{person1.name}}, {{person1.name}}</div>
<div @if(person2)>{{person2.name}}, {{person2.name}}</div>
<div @if(person3)>{{person3.name}}, {{person3.name}}</div>
``` 

### Alternatives considered

Alternatively use the old syntax

```
@if (person1) {
  <div>{{person1.name}}, {{person1.name}}</div>
}
@if (person2) {
  <div>{{person2.name}}, {{person2.name}}</div>
}
@if (person3) {
  <div>{{person3.name}}, {{person3.name}}</div>
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

`@angular/router`

### Description

in 18.1.0, we can set a different browser URL from the one for route matching via Router's navigate & navigateByUrl methods, this is a very exciting feature. thank you to the NG team.

```
router.navigateByUrl('/404', {
    browserUrl: router.getCurrentNavigation()?.finalUrl,
});
``` 

We can subscribe router.events to receive various routing and navigation events
```
router.events.subscribe(event => {
  if (event instanceof NavigationStart) {
   // do somethings
 });
```

In the micro frontend architecture of multiple NG applications, it is necessary to subscribe to router events to synchronize the router of other applications, which can cause the browserURL to be modified by the router of other NG application and become invalid. therefore, it is necessary to determine whether the browserURL has been set in the event.

### Proposed solution

NavigationStart and NavigationEnd add `browserUrl?: string` 

### Alternatives considered

NavigationStart and NavigationEnd add `behaviorOptions?: NavigationBehaviorOptions`

